{"title_page": "Kajagoogoo", "text_new": "{{short description|British new wave band}}\n{{EngvarB|date=May 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2015}}\n{{Refimprove|date=May 2009}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name                = Kajagoogoo\n| image               = Kajagoogoo_in_Germany_Bochum_2008.jpg\n| caption             = Kajagoogoo in Bochum, Germany; 2008.  L-R: Nick Beggs, Stuart Croxford Neale, Limahl, Jez Strode and Steve Askew.\n| background          = group_or_band\n| alias               = {{ubl|Art Nouveau <small>(1978\u20131981)</small>|Kaja <small>(1984\u20131985)</small>}}\n| origin              = [[Leighton Buzzard]], Bedfordshire, England\n| genre               = [[New wave music|New wave]], [[synthpop]], [[pop rock]]\n| years_active        = 1978\u20131985, 2003\u20132004, 2007\u20132011\n| label               = [[EMI Records|EMI]], [[Parlophone]], Spectra\n| associated_acts     = \n| website             = {{URL|www.kajagoogoo.com}}\n| past_members     = {{ubl|[[Steve Askew]]|[[Nick Beggs]]|Stuart Neale|[[Jez Strode]]|[[Limahl]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Kajagoogoo''' {{IPAc-en|k|\u00e6|d\u0292|\u0259|\u02c8|g|u\u02d0|g|u\u02d0|}} were a British [[New wave music|new wave]] band, best known for their 1983 hit single \"[[Too Shy]]\", which reached No.&nbsp;1 in the [[UK Singles Chart]],<ref name=\"British Hit Singles & Albums\">{{cite book| first= David\n| last= Roberts| year= 2006| title= [[British Hit Singles & Albums]]| edition= 19| publisher= Guinness World Records Limited | location= London\n| isbn= 978-1-904994-10-7| page= 295}}</ref> and the Top 10 in numerous other countries. Throughout the first half of the 1980s, the band also enjoyed a number of smaller chart successes in multiple markets.\n\n==History==\n===Beginnings (1978\u20131982)===\nFormed in [[Leighton Buzzard]], [[Bedfordshire]] in 1978, the band were originally known as '''Art Nouveau''', a four-piece [[avant-garde]] group, with [[Nick Beggs]] on bass guitar, [[Steve Askew]] on lead guitar, Stuart Croxford Neale on keyboards, and [[Jez Strode|Jeremy \"Jez\" Strode]] on drums. Art Nouveau released a track called \"The Fear Machine\", which sold a few hundred copies and enjoyed airtime on [[John Peel|John Peel's]] show. In spite of the song's success, the band failed to secure a record deal during this period.\n\nIn 1981, Art Noveau advertised for a new lead singer. They ultimately auditioned and choose [[Limahl|Christopher Hamill]], who then went under the stage name Limahl (an [[anagram]] of his surname). The group renamed themselves '''Kajagoogoo''', a name coined [[Phonetics|phonetically]] from ''ga ga goo goo'', the first sounds that many infants make.<ref name=\"kajagoogoo1\">{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.kajagoogoo.com/ |title=Kajagoogoo.com |publisher=Kajagoogoo.com |date= |accessdate=14 December 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Success and decline (1982\u20131985)===\nThe band signed with [[EMI Records]] in July 1982 after Limahl had met keyboardist [[Nick Rhodes]] of the group [[Duran Duran]] while working as a waiter at London's Embassy Club.<ref>The Very Best of Kajagoogoo \u2013 liner notes (Chris White, 1996, EMI Gold \u2013 Cat no.724385295621)</ref> Rhodes proceeded to co-produce the band's first single, \"[[Too Shy]]\" with Duran Duran's EMI producer [[Colin Thurston]]. The single was released on 10 January 1983 and topped the [[UK Singles Chart]]<ref name=\"British Hit Singles & Albums\"/>, having done so before any of Duran Duran's singles (as Rhodes himself has lightheartedly noted).\n\nFollow-up singles \"Ooh to Be Aah\" and \"Hang on Now\" also both reached the [[UK Top 40|UK Top 20]], and the group's debut album ''[[White Feathers]]'' reached No. 5 in the [[UK Albums Chart]].<ref name=\"British Hit Singles & Albums\"/> After being the support act for the [[Birmingham]] band [[Fashion (band)|Fashion]] in late 1982, Kajagoogoo embarked on their own headlining ''White Feathers'' tour in Spring 1983. Their performance on 31 May at the [[Hammersmith Odeon|London Hammersmith Odeon]] was filmed and released on home video.\n\nAs success came, tensions began to rise in the band. These tensions culminated in Limahl being fired by the other band members in mid-1983 and Nick Beggs then taking over as lead singer. In response to his ousting, Limahl accused the others of being envious of him and said \"I've been betrayed!\" and \"I was sacked for making them a success.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ukfestivalguides.com/artist/limahl |title=Limahl \u2013 Latest festivals, news, tickets and more |publisher=Ukfestivalguides.com |date=19 December 1958 |accessdate=14 December 2012}}</ref> The other band members countered Limahl's assertions, insisting that he had become egomaniacal and increasingly difficult to work with. Soon after the departure, Beggs commented, \"It was a business decision and not one we took lightly. He wanted the band to go in a different direction to the rest of us. Eventually, we realised we were on a different planet to Limahl.\"<ref name=\"Smash Hits\">{{cite magazine |last1= Steels|first1= Deborah|last2= |first2= |title= The Fruit Case (Kajagoogoo interview))|magazine= Smash Hits|volume= 5|issue= 19|pages=41\u201342|publisher= EMAP Metro|date=15 September 1983}}</ref> Beggs also stated that the band harboured no ill-will towards Limahl, and blamed the press for sensationalising the matter. Guitarist Steve Askew commented \"At first ... we did everything possible to make Limahl feel like part of the furniture but, you know, his lifestyle is so different from ours. We're very normal people whereas Limahl likes the bright lights.\"<ref name=\"Smash Hits\"/>\n\nThe first single by the new four-piece lineup, \"[[Big Apple (song)|Big Apple]]\", was released in September 1983 and reached the UK Top Ten. Their next single, \"The Lion's Mouth\", was released in February 1984 and made the UK Top 30,<ref name=\"British Hit Singles & Albums\"/>. After this, public interest in the group waned, and their next single \"[[Turn Your Back on Me (song)|Turn Your Back On Me]]\" failed to make the Top 40. The subsequent new album, ''[[Islands (Kajagoogoo album)|Islands]]'', was also a commercial disappointment, peaking at No. 35 in the UK.<ref name=\"British Hit Singles & Albums\"/>\n\nIn the US, the band first adopted the '''Kaja''' moniker at this time, and a different edition of the ''Islands'' album was released there as ''[[Islands (Kajagoogoo album)|Extra Play]]'', peaking at No. 185 on the Billboard charts. However, the single \"Turn Your Back on Me\" did well on the US Dance Charts, peaking at No. 2 for two weeks.<ref>{{cite book |title= Hot Dance/Disco: 1974\u20132003|last=Whitburn |first=Joel |authorlink=Joel Whitburn |year=2004 |publisher=Record Research |page=141}}</ref> Meanwhile, Limahl went on to equally brief success as a solo artist and Strode left the band.\n\nIn an attempt to regain credibility and lose their light-hearted, [[Bubblegum pop|bubblegum]] image, the remaining three members relaunched as '''Kaja''' in the UK in 1985. Following the name change, the band released the single \"Shouldn't Do That\" (UK No.&nbsp;63) in August 1985.<ref name=\"British Hit Singles & Albums\"/> The song was featured on their third album, ''[[Crazy People's Right to Speak]]''. After this proved unsuccessful, the group disbanded in December 1985.<ref>\"Kaja Go-Go\", ''[[Sounds (magazine)|Sounds]]'', 14 December 1985, p. 4</ref>\n\n===Reunions (2003\u20132011)===\nThe original five-piece line-up of the band briefly joined forces again on [[VH1]]'s ''[[Bands Reunited]]'' in 2003.\n\nFollowing the much publicised VH1 reunion, the original group received many offers and incentives to continue to play together,<ref name=\"kajagoogoo1\"/> but disagreements continued between the band members and the reunion was short-lived, as Limahl and Strode both departed the band again shortly thereafter, ultimately leading them to dissolve the following year. The group felt that the VH1 feature was unfairly edited to portray simplified reasons as to why Limahl was fired and Strode had left the band in the 1980s.<ref name=\"kajagoogoo1\"/>\n\nIn 2007, Nick Beggs, Steve Askew, and Stuart Neale decided to continue as Kajagoogoo, releasing the single \"Rocket Boy\" on 24 June 2007. The single received airplay on [[Steve Wright (DJ)|Steve Wright]]'s [[BBC Radio 2]] show in the UK, and a new album, ''[[Gone to the Moon]]'', was scheduled for release on the Spectra Records label later on that year. However, the album was postponed, and in February 2008, the three Kajagoogoo members announced plans to reunite with original members singer Limahl and drummer Jez Strode. This was due in part to Bradley Snelling, the organiser of the Retrofest event and the band's new manager. Snelling had succeeded in reuniting the band, arranging their first [[photo shoot]] together in 25 years.\n\nThe band wrote on their official site that \"[t]he atmosphere was relaxed, jovial and, after 25 years, Kajagoogoo, in their original five-piece line-up are back\". After reforming, the band wrote new material, released an EP, and toured extensively throughout Europe, performing first in Denmark on 14 June 2008, at [[Esbjerg]] [[Rock Festival]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.esbjergrockfestival.dk/ |title=Esbjerg Rock Festival |publisher=Esbjergrockfestival.dk |date= |accessdate=14 December 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080620025048/http://www.esbjergrockfestival.dk/ |archive-date=20 June 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref> where they performed the 16 tracks off the remastered edition of ''[[Islands (Kajagoogoo album)|Islands]]'', including encores and B-sides, such as \"Monochromatic\" or \"The Garden\"). Their ''Gone to the Moon'' album, recorded as a three-piece outfit prior to the full reunion, was distributed via the live shows and \"Kajashop\", the band's online store.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.kajashop.co.uk/ |title=Kajagoogoo |publisher=Kajashop.co.uk |accessdate=14 December 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130129040329/http://www.kajashop.co.uk/ |archivedate=29 January 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn August 2009 while in the middle of a tour, Kajagoogoo again took to the stage to headline the 'Hobble on The Cobbles' all day music event in [[Aylesbury]] in Buckinghamshire. This was followed in September by a new compilation CD/DVD, released by the band's original label EMI Records, called ''Too Shy \u2013 The Best of Kajagoogoo & Limahl''. It featured two newly recorded tracks, plus a brand new promotional video for \"Space Cadet\", one of the new recordings. Quick to capitalise on the renewed interest in the band, EMI released the \"White Feathers (Manhattan Clique Remixes) EP\" in December 2009.\n\nIn December 2009, Kajagoogoo performed their last remaining UK concert with a return to The Stables venue in Wavendon, Milton Keynes. In March 2010, dPulse Recordings released the Kajagoogoo track \"First Girl on Mars\" as a part of the ''Who Made Your Music?'' benefit CD, released to raise funds and bring awareness to the rights of marginalised women.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.whomadeyourpants.co.uk/ |title=Who Made Your Pants? |publisher=Whomadeyourpants.co.uk |accessdate=14 December 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130116204113/http://www.whomadeyourpants.co.uk/ |archivedate=16 January 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> On Saturday 17 July 2010, Kajagoogoo performed at the Midland Music Festival in Tamworth and later performed at the Rewind Festival in Henley-on-Thames in August. Continuing to capitalise on renewed interest in the Kajagoogoo back catalogue, EMI Records released ''So80s Presents Kajagoogoo'' as a part of the ''So Eighties'' series curated by Blank & Jones. The album contains extended mixes of classic Kajagoogoo tracks and was released on CD and digital download format. Also made available digitally in April 2011, Kajagoogoo's ''Gone to the Moon'' album was given a digital release via iTunes.\n\nIn June 2011, Kajagoogoo released their first single as a five piece since 1983. The track, \"Death Defying Headlines\", was released as a digital single as both a single edit and an extended dance remix.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://kajagoogoo.com |title=Kajagoogoo |publisher=Kajagoogoo.com |date= |accessdate=14 December 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2017, bassist Nick Beggs said that Kajagoogoo was no longer active, stating \"We did something about nine years ago, and that was good. It was almost like a kind of revisiting of it for old time\u2019s sake and I felt that we did quite a lot of good with that. But in terms of moving forward, there\u2019s no point in revisiting that project.\"<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://progressivemusicreview.wordpress.com/2017/03/09/new-nick-beggs-interview-march-2017/\n|title=New Nick Beggs Interview \u2013 March 2017 |publisher=Progressive Music Review |date= |accessdate=10 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn an interview with Cherry Red TV in 2018, Beggs talked about the reunion, stating \"...we reformed and we toured and we recorded an EP and remastered the back catalogue...and at that point I felt that we had done it all. It was a nice way to tie it up, put a bow on it and leave it alone and move on.\"\n\n==Members==\n*[[Steve Askew]] \u2013 guitars, programming, backing vocals <small>(1978\u20131985, 2003\u20132004, 2007\u20132011)</small>\n*[[Nick Beggs]] \u2013 bass guitar, Chapman Stick, guitars, keyboards, programming, percussion, backing vocals <small>(1978\u20131985, 2003\u20132004, 2007\u20132011)</small>, lead vocals <small>(1978\u20131982, 1983\u20131985, 2003\u20132004, 2007\u20132011)</small>\n*Stuart Neale \u2013 keyboards, programming, piano, backing vocals <small>(1978\u20131985, 2003\u20132004, 2007\u20132011)</small>\n*[[Jez Strode]] \u2013 acoustic and electronic drums, percussion <small>(1978\u20131984, 2003, 2008\u20132011)</small>\n*[[Limahl]] (Chris Hamill) \u2013 lead vocals <small>(1982\u20131983, 2003, 2008\u20132011)</small>\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|Kajagoogoo discography}}\n\n===Studio albums===\n*''[[White Feathers]]'' (1983)\n*''[[Islands (Kajagoogoo album)|Islands]]'' (1984)\n*''[[Crazy Peoples Right to Speak]]''  (1985) <small>as Kaja</small>\n*''[[Gone to the Moon]]'' (2008)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|35em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* Paul Gambaccini (1983), ''Kajagoogoo''\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.kajagoogoo.com The Official Kajagoogoo Website]\n\n{{Kajagoogoo}}\n{{Limahl}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:English new wave musical groups]]\n[[Category:English dance music groups]]\n[[Category:English pop music groups]]\n[[Category:British synth-pop new wave groups]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 1978]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 1982]]\n[[Category:Musical groups disestablished in 1985]]\n[[Category:Musical groups reestablished in 2003]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British new wave band}}\n{{EngvarB|date=May 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2015}}\n{{Refimprove|date=May 2009}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name                = Kajagoogoo\n| image               = Kajagoogoo_in_Germany_Bochum_2008.jpg\n| caption             = Kajagoogoo in Bochum, Germany; 2008.  L-R: Nick Beggs, Stuart Croxford Neale, Limahl, Jez Strode and Steve Askew.\n| background          = group_or_band\n| alias               = {{ubl|Art Nouveau <small>(1978\u20131981)</small>|Kaja <small>(1984\u20131985)</small>}}\n| origin              = [[Leighton Buzzard]], Bedfordshire, England\n| genre               = [[New wave music|New wave]], [[synthpop]], [[pop rock]]\n| years_active        = 1978\u20131985, 2003\u20132004, 2007\u20132011\n| label               = [[EMI Records|EMI]], [[Parlophone]], Spectra\n| associated_acts     = \n| website             = {{URL|www.kajagoogoo.com}}\n| past_members     = {{ubl|[[Steve Askew]]|[[Nick Beggs]]|Stuart Neale|[[Jez Strode]]|[[Limahl]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Kajagoogoo''' {{IPAc-en|k|\u00e6|d\u0292|\u0259|\u02c8|g|u\u02d0|g|u\u02d0|}} were a British [[New wave music|new wave]] band, best known for their 1983 hit single \"[[Too Shy]]\", which reached No.&nbsp;1 in the [[UK Singles Chart]],<ref name=\"British Hit Singles & Albums\">{{cite book| first= David\n| last= Roberts| year= 2006| title= [[British Hit Singles & Albums]]| edition= 19| publisher= Guinness World Records Limited | location= London\n| isbn= 978-1-904994-10-7| page= 295}}</ref> and the Top 10 in numerous other countries.\n\n==History==\n===Beginnings (1978\u20131982)===\nFormed in [[Leighton Buzzard]] in 1978, the band were originally known as '''Art Nouveau''', a four-piece [[avant-garde]] group, with [[Nick Beggs]] on bass guitar, [[Steve Askew]] on lead guitar, Stuart Croxford Neale on keyboards, and [[Jez Strode|Jeremy \"Jez\" Strode]] on drums. Art Nouveau released a track called \"The Fear Machine\". The single sold a few hundred copies, and was played on the [[John Peel]] show, but the band was unable to get a record deal.\n\nIn 1981, they advertised for a new lead singer, ultimately auditioning and choosing [[Limahl|Christopher Hamill]], who then went under the stage name Limahl (an anagram of his surname). The name of the group was then changed to '''Kajagoogoo''', coined [[phonetic]]ally from a baby's first sounds, 'Ga Ga Goo Goo'.<ref name=\"kajagoogoo1\">{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.kajagoogoo.com/ |title=Kajagoogoo.com |publisher=Kajagoogoo.com |date= |accessdate=14 December 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Success and decline (1982\u20131985)===\nThe band signed with [[EMI Records]] in July 1982 after Limahl, while working as a waiter at London's Embassy Club, had met [[Nick Rhodes]] of the group [[Duran Duran]].<ref>The Very Best of Kajagoogoo \u2013 liner notes (Chris White, 1996, EMI Gold \u2013 Cat no.724385295621)</ref> Rhodes proceeded to co-produce the band's first single, \"[[Too Shy]]\" with Duran Duran's EMI producer [[Colin Thurston]]. The single was released on 10 January 1983 and went on to top the [[UK Singles Chart]]<ref name=\"British Hit Singles & Albums\"/> (before any of Duran Duran's singles had done so, Rhodes lightheartedly noted).\n\nFollow-up singles \"Ooh to Be Aah\" and \"Hang on Now\" also both reached the [[UK Top 40|UK Top 20]], and the group's debut album ''[[White Feathers]]'' reached No. 5 in the [[UK Albums Chart]].<ref name=\"British Hit Singles & Albums\"/> After being the support act for the [[Birmingham]] band [[Fashion (band)|Fashion]] in late 1982, Kajagoogoo embarked on their own headlining ''White Feathers'' tour in Spring 1983 (with the show of 31 May at the [[Hammersmith Odeon|London Hammersmith Odeon]] being filmed and released on home video).\n\nAs success came, tensions began to rise in the band, which eventually culminated in Limahl being fired by the other band members in mid-1983 and Nick Beggs then taking over as lead singer. Limahl accused the others of being envious of him and said \"I've been betrayed!\" and \"I was sacked for making them a success.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ukfestivalguides.com/artist/limahl |title=Limahl \u2013 Latest festivals, news, tickets and more |publisher=Ukfestivalguides.com |date=19 December 1958 |accessdate=14 December 2012}}</ref> However, the other band members went on record as saying that Limahl was an egomaniac and had become increasingly difficult to work with. Soon after Limahl's departure, Beggs commented that \"It was a business decision and not one we took lightly. He wanted the band to go in a different direction to the rest of us. Eventually, we realised we were on a different planet to Limahl.\"<ref name=\"Smash Hits\">{{cite magazine |last1= Steels|first1= Deborah|last2= |first2= |title= The Fruit Case (Kajagoogoo interview))|magazine= Smash Hits|volume= 5|issue= 19|pages=41\u201342|publisher= EMAP Metro|date=15 September 1983}}</ref> Beggs also stated that the band harboured no ill-will towards Limahl, and blamed the press for sensationalising the matter. Guitarist Steve Askew commented \"At first ... we did everything possible to make Limahl feel like part of the furniture but, you know, his lifestyle is so different from ours. We're very normal people whereas Limahl likes the bright lights.\"<ref name=\"Smash Hits\"/>\n\nThe first single by the new four-piece Kajagoogoo, \"[[Big Apple (song)|Big Apple]]\", was released in September 1983 and reached the UK Top Ten. Their next single, \"The Lion's Mouth\", was released in February 1984 and made the UK Top 30,<ref name=\"British Hit Singles & Albums\"/> but after that public interest waned and their next single \"[[Turn Your Back on Me (song)|Turn Your Back On Me]]\" failed to make the Top 40. The subsequent new album, ''[[Islands (Kajagoogoo album)|Islands]]'', was also a commercial disappointment, peaking at No. 35 in the UK.<ref name=\"British Hit Singles & Albums\"/>\n\nIn the US, the band first adopted the '''Kaja''' moniker at this time, and a different edition of the ''Islands'' album was released there as ''[[Islands (Kajagoogoo album)|Extra Play]]'', peaking at No. 185 on the Billboard charts. However, the single \"Turn Your Back on Me\" did well on the US Dance Charts peaking at No. 2 for two weeks.<ref>{{cite book |title= Hot Dance/Disco: 1974\u20132003|last=Whitburn |first=Joel |authorlink=Joel Whitburn |year=2004 |publisher=Record Research |page=141}}</ref> Limahl, meanwhile, went on to equally brief success as a solo artist.\n\nStrode then left the band and, in an attempt to gain some credibility and to lose their bubblegum image, the remaining three members relaunched as '''Kaja''' in the UK in 1985. Following the name change, the band released the single \"Shouldn't Do That\" (UK No.&nbsp;63) in August 1985.<ref name=\"British Hit Singles & Albums\"/> The song was featured on their third album, ''[[Crazy People's Right to Speak]]'', but this too was unsuccessful. In December 1985, the band split up.<ref>\"Kaja Go-Go\", ''[[Sounds (magazine)|Sounds]]'', 14 December 1985, p. 4</ref>\n\n===Reunion (2003\u20132011)===\nThe original five-piece line-up of the band briefly joined forces again on [[VH1]]'s ''[[Bands Reunited]]'' in 2003. Following the much publicised VH1 reunion, the original group received many offers and incentives to continue to play together,<ref name=\"kajagoogoo1\"/> but disagreements continued between the band members and the reunion was short-lived; with Limahl and Strode both departing the band again shortly thereafter, ultimately leading to the group dissolving the following year. The group felt that the VH1 feature was unfairly edited to portray simplified reasons as to why Limahl was fired and Strode had left the band in the 1980s.<ref name=\"kajagoogoo1\"/>\n\nIn 2007, Nick Beggs, Steve Askew, and Stuart Neale decided to continue the Kajagoogoo reunion, releasing the single \"Rocket Boy\" on 24 June 2007. The single received airplay on [[Steve Wright (DJ)|Steve Wright]]'s [[BBC Radio 2]] show in the UK, and a new album, ''[[Gone to the Moon]]'', was scheduled for release on the Spectra Records label later on that year. However, the album was postponed and in February 2008, the three Kajagoogoo members announced plans to reunite with original members singer Limahl and drummer Jez Strode. This was due in part to Bradley Snelling, the organiser of the Retrofest event and the band's new manager. Snelling had succeeded in reuniting the band, arranging their first [[photo shoot]] together in 25 years.\n\nThe band wrote on their official site that \"The atmosphere was relaxed, jovial and, after 25 years, Kajagoogoo, in their original five-piece line-up are back\". Since reforming, the band have written new material, released an EP, and have extensively toured throughout Europe (with the first date taking place in Denmark on 14 June 2008, at [[Esbjerg]] [[Rock Festival]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.esbjergrockfestival.dk/ |title=Esbjerg Rock Festival |publisher=Esbjergrockfestival.dk |date= |accessdate=14 December 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080620025048/http://www.esbjergrockfestival.dk/ |archive-date=20 June 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref> where they performed the 16 tracks off the remastered edition of ''[[Islands (Kajagoogoo album)|Islands]]'', including encores and B-sides, such as \"Monochromatic\" or \"The Garden\"). Their ''Gone to the Moon'' album, recorded as a three-piece outfit prior to the full reunion, was made available via the live shows and \"Kajashop\", the band's online store.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.kajashop.co.uk/ |title=Kajagoogoo |publisher=Kajashop.co.uk |accessdate=14 December 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130129040329/http://www.kajashop.co.uk/ |archivedate=29 January 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn August 2009 and in addition to the reunion tour commitments, Kajagoogoo again took to the stage to headline the 'Hobble on The Cobbles' all day music event in [[Aylesbury]] in Buckinghamshire. This was followed in September by a new compilation CD/DVD, released by the band's original label EMI Records, called ''Too Shy \u2013 The Best of Kajagoogoo & Limahl''. It featured two newly recorded tracks, plus a brand new promotional video for \"Space Cadet\", one of the new recordings. Quick to capitalise on the renewed interest in the band, EMI released the \"White Feathers (Manhattan Clique Remixes) EP\" in December 2009.\n\nIn December 2009, Kajagoogoo performed their last remaining UK concert with a return to The Stables venue in Wavendon, Milton Keynes. In March 2010, dPulse Recordings released the Kajagoogoo track \"First Girl on Mars\" as a part of the ''Who Made Your Music?'' benefit CD, released to raise funds and bring awareness to the rights of marginalised women.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.whomadeyourpants.co.uk/ |title=Who Made Your Pants? |publisher=Whomadeyourpants.co.uk |accessdate=14 December 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130116204113/http://www.whomadeyourpants.co.uk/ |archivedate=16 January 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> On Saturday 17 July 2010, Kajagoogoo performed at the Midland Music Festival in Tamworth, and later performed at the Rewind Festival in Henley-on-Thames in August. Continuing their renewed interest in the Kajagoogoo back catalogue, EMI Records released ''So80s Presents Kajagoogoo'' as a part of the ''So Eighties'' series curated by Blank & Jones. The album contains extended mixes of classic Kajagoogoo tracks and was released on CD and digital download format. Also made available digitally in April 2011, Kajagoogoo's ''Gone to the Moon'' album was given a digital release via iTunes.\n\nIn June 2011, Kajagoogoo released their first single as a five piece since 1983. The track, \"Death Defying Headlines\", was released as a digital single as both a single edit and an extended dance remix.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://kajagoogoo.com |title=Kajagoogoo |publisher=Kajagoogoo.com |date= |accessdate=14 December 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2017, bassist Nick Beggs said that Kajagoogoo was no longer active, stating \"We did something about nine years ago, and that was good. It was almost like a kind of revisiting of it for old time\u2019s sake and I felt that we did quite a lot of good with that. But in terms of moving forward, there\u2019s no point in revisiting that project.\"<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://progressivemusicreview.wordpress.com/2017/03/09/new-nick-beggs-interview-march-2017/\n|title=New Nick Beggs Interview \u2013 March 2017 |publisher=Progressive Music Review |date= |accessdate=10 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn an interview with Cherry Red TV in 2018, Beggs talked about the reunion, stating \"...we reformed and we toured and we recorded an EP and remastered the back catalogue...and at that point I felt that we had done it all. It was a nice way to tie it up, put a bow on it and leave it alone and move on.\"\n\n==Members==\n*[[Steve Askew]] \u2013 guitars, programming, backing vocals <small>(1978\u20131985, 2003\u20132004, 2007\u20132011)</small>\n*[[Nick Beggs]] \u2013 bass guitar, Chapman Stick, guitars, keyboards, programming, percussion, backing vocals <small>(1978\u20131985, 2003\u20132004, 2007\u20132011)</small>, lead vocals <small>(1978\u20131982, 1983\u20131985, 2003\u20132004, 2007\u20132011)</small>\n*Stuart Neale \u2013 keyboards, programming, piano, backing vocals <small>(1978\u20131985, 2003\u20132004, 2007\u20132011)</small>\n*[[Jez Strode]] \u2013 acoustic and electronic drums, percussion <small>(1978\u20131984, 2003, 2008\u20132011)</small>\n*[[Limahl]] (Chris Hamill) \u2013 lead vocals <small>(1982\u20131983, 2003, 2008\u20132011)</small>\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|Kajagoogoo discography}}\n\n===Studio albums===\n*''[[White Feathers]]'' (1983)\n*''[[Islands (Kajagoogoo album)|Islands]]'' (1984)\n*''[[Crazy Peoples Right to Speak]]''  (1985) <small>as Kaja</small>\n*''[[Gone to the Moon]]'' (2008)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|35em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* Paul Gambaccini (1983), ''Kajagoogoo''\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.kajagoogoo.com The Official Kajagoogoo Website]\n\n{{Kajagoogoo}}\n{{Limahl}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:English new wave musical groups]]\n[[Category:English dance music groups]]\n[[Category:English pop music groups]]\n[[Category:British synth-pop new wave groups]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 1978]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 1982]]\n[[Category:Musical groups disestablished in 1985]]\n[[Category:Musical groups reestablished in 2003]]\n", "name_user": "2600:6c50:4d00:1547:4518:81fb:9ccd:aba9", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kajagoogoo"}
{"title_page": "New Flemish Alliance", "text_new": "{{Update|inaccurate=yes|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox political party\n| name = New Flemish Alliance\n| native_name = Nieuw-Vlaamse Alliantie\n| logo = [[File:FileLogo N-VA (Nieuw-Vlaamse Alliantie).png|260px]]\n| leader = [[Bart De Wever]]\n| founder = [[Geert Bourgeois]]\n| foundation = 2001\n| split = [[People's Union (Belgium)|People's Union]]\n| colorcode = {{New_Flemish_Alliance/meta/color}}\n| membership_year = 2018\n| membership = {{increase}} 45,000<ref>{{cite news|url=http://deredactie.be/permalink/1.2133806|title= Open VLD heeft de meeste leden en steekt CD&V voorbij|publisher=deredactie.be|date=30 October 2014}}</ref>\n| ideology = [[Flemish Movement|Flemish nationalism]]<ref name=\"Sarat2013\"/><br />[[Regionalism (politics)|Regionalism]]<ref name=\"Dandoy2013\">{{cite book|author= R\u00e9gis Dandoy|chapter=Belgium|editor1=R\u00e9gis Dandoy|editor2=Arjan Schakel|title=Regional and National Elections in Western Europe: Territoriality of the Vote in Thirteen Countries|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9-GxAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA54|year=2013|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|isbn=978-1-137-02544-9|page=54}}</ref><br />[[Separatism]]<ref name=\"Nordsieck\"/><ref name=\"demsoc\">{{cite web|url=http://www.demsoc.org/2014/02/06/new-flemish-alliance/|title=New Flemish Alliance|publisher=The Democratic Society|date=6 February 2014|last=Terry|first=Chris}}</ref><br />[[Conservatism]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politico.eu/article/belgium-bart-de-wever-government-flemish-nationalism-n-va-migration-terrorism/|title=Belgium\u2019s Mr. Right|date=3 December 2015|publisher=}}</ref><br />[[Liberal conservatism]]<ref name=\"Nordsieck\">{{cite web|first=Wolfram|last=Nordsieck|url=http://www.parties-and-elections.eu/flanders.html|title=Flanders/Belgium|website=Parties and Elections in Europe|year=2019|accessdate=30 May 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"demsoc\"/><br />[[Soft Euroscepticism]]<ref name=\"De Standaard\"/><br>'''Historical:'''<br>[[Pro-Europeanism]]<ref name=\"euobserver\"/><ref name=\"blogs.lse.ac.uk\"/>\n| position = {{nowrap|[[Centre-right politics|Centre-right]]<ref name=\"MoufahimHumphreys2015\">{{cite book|author1=Mona Moufahim|author2=Michael Humphreys|chapter=Marketing an extremist ideology: the Vlaams Belang's nationalist discourse|editor1=Alison Pullen|editor2=Carl Rhodes|title=The Routledge Companion to Ethics, Politics and Organizations|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9SrLCQAAQBAJ&pg=PA90|year=2015|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-136-74624-6|page=90}}</ref> to [[Right-wing politics|right-wing]]<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=ywJdBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA145&lpg=PA145&dq=Right-wing+Flemish+Interest&source=bl&ots=8hUY4tBhgb&sig=AJ8-_1MesQBAQopBeitUKKHvYxY&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiY9sKgnO3QAhWOM1AKHXrNBzM4ChDoAQhXMAg#v=onepage&q&f=false Political Geography]<br />p.145<br />Google Books.<br />Authors - Joe Painter and Alex Jeffery.<br />Published by Sage in Los Angeles, United States.<br />First published in 2009.</ref>}}\n| european = {{nowrap|[[European Free Alliance]]}}\n| europarl = [[European Conservatives and Reformists]]\n| colors = {{Color box|#000|border=darkgray}} Black<br />{{Color box|{{New_Flemish_Alliance/meta/color}}|border=darkgray}} Gold\n| headquarters = Koningsstraat 47, bus 6<br />B-1000 Brussels\n| website = {{url|http://www.n-va.be/}}\n| country = Belgium\n| seats1_title = [[Chamber of Representatives (Belgium)|Chamber of Representatives]]<br />(Flemish seats)\n| seats1 = {{Composition bar|25|87|hex={{New_Flemish_Alliance/meta/color}}}}\n| seats2_title = [[Senate (Belgium)|Senate]]<br />(Flemish seats)\n| seats2 = {{Composition bar|9|35|hex={{New_Flemish_Alliance/meta/color}}}}\n| seats3_title = [[Flemish Parliament]]\n| seats3 = {{Composition bar|35|124|hex={{New_Flemish_Alliance/meta/color}}}}\n| seats4_title = [[Parliament of the Brussels-Capital Region|Brussels Parliament]]<br />(Flemish seats)\n| seats4 = {{Composition bar|3|17|hex={{New_Flemish_Alliance/meta/color}}}}\n| seats5_title = [[European&nbsp;Parliament]]<br />([[Dutch-speaking electoral college|Flemish seats]])\n| seats5 = {{Composition bar|3|12|hex={{New_Flemish_Alliance/meta/color}}}}\n| seats6_title = [[Provinces of Belgium|Flemish Provincial Councils]]\n| seats6 = {{Composition bar|46|175|hex={{New_Flemish_Alliance/meta/color}}}}\n}}\n\nThe '''New Flemish Alliance''' ({{lang-nl|Nieuw-Vlaamse Alliantie}}, '''N-VA''')<ref>'''Pronunciation: {{Audio|Nl-Nieuw-Vlaamse Alliantie.ogg|Nieuw-Vlaamse Alliantie|help=no}}'''</ref> is a [[Flemish Movement|Flemish nationalist]],<ref name=\"Sarat2013\">{{cite book|author1=Sara Wallace Goodman|author2=Marc Morj\u00e9 Howard|chapter=Evaluating and explaining the restrictive backlash in citizenship policy in Europe|editor=Austin Sarat|title=Special Issue: Immigration, Citizenship, and the Constitution of Legality|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RqBlR1LQIpYC&pg=PA132|year=2013|publisher=Emerald Group Publishing|isbn=978-1-78190-431-2|page=132}}</ref> [[Conservatism|conservative]]<ref name=\"BuelensDeschouwer2007\">{{cite book|author1=Jo Buelens|author2=Kris Deschouwer|chapter=Torn Between Two Levels: Political Parties and Incongruent Coalitions in Belgium|editor1=Kris Deschouwer|editor2=M. Theo Jans|title=Politics Beyond the State: Actors and Policies in Complex Institutional Settings|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ETmOOM8eTfUC&pg=PA75|year=2007|publisher=Asp / Vubpress / Upa|isbn=978-90-5487-436-2|page=75}}</ref><ref name=\"Slomp2011\">{{cite book|author=Hans Slomp|title=Europe, a Political Profile: An American Companion to European Politics|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=V1uzkNq8xfIC&pg=PA465|year=2011|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-0-313-39181-1|page=465}}</ref><ref name=\"Sorens2013\">{{cite book|author=Jason Sorens|chapter=The Partisan Logic of Decentralization in Europe|editor1=Jan Erk|editor2=Lawrence M. Anderson|title=PARADOX FEDERALISM|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QfjaAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA73|year=2013|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-317-98772-7|page=73}}</ref> [[Political parties in Belgium|political party]] in Belgium, founded in 2001 after it split from the [[People's Union (Belgium)|People's Union]].<ref name=\"englishpage\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20100522055224/http://www.n-va.be:80/english n-va.be, english information page]</ref> The N-VA is a [[Regionalism (politics)|regionalist]],<ref name=\"StarkeKaasch2013\">{{cite book|author1=Peter Starke|author2=Alexandra Kaasch|author3=Franca Van Hooren|title=The Welfare State as Crisis Manager: Explaining the Diversity of Policy Responses to Economic Crisis|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BtMQsESYcWwC&pg=PA192|date=7 May 2013|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|isbn=978-1-137-31484-0|page=192}}</ref> [[Separatism|separatist]]<ref name=\"Kataria2011\">{{cite book|author=Anuradha Kataria|title=Democracy on Trial, All Rise!|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=F-CWfWLmSl0C&pg=PA119|year=2011|publisher=Algora Publishing|isbn=978-0-87586-811-0|page=119}}</ref><ref name=\"Johnston2011\">{{cite book|author=Larry Johnston|title=Politics: An Introduction to the Modern Democratic State|url=https://archive.org/details/politicsintroduc0000john_l7q9|url-access=registration|date=13 December 2011|publisher=University of Toronto Press|isbn=978-1-4426-0533-6|page=[https://archive.org/details/politicsintroduc0000john_l7q9/page/256 256]}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=European Politics|year=2007|url=https://archive.org/details/europeanpolitics00hayc|url-access=registration|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-928428-3|page=[https://archive.org/details/europeanpolitics00hayc/page/92 92]}}</ref><ref name=\"Inc.2011\">{{cite book|author=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica, Inc.|title=Britannica Book of the Year 2011|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mfecAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA29|date=1 March 2011|publisher=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica, Inc.|isbn=978-1-61535-500-6|page=29}}</ref> movement that self-identifies with the promotion of [[civic nationalism]].<ref name=\"ManifestPoint13\">[http://www.n-va.be/files/default/nva_images/documenten/manifest.pdf Manifesto of the New Flemish Alliance] point 13: \"Inclusion for newcommers\" (in Dutch).</ref> It is part of the [[Flemish Movement]]; the party strives for the peaceful<ref name=\"ManifestPoint6\">[http://www.n-va.be/files/default/nva_images/documenten/manifest.pdf Manifesto of the New Flemish Alliance] point 6: \"Pacifisme\" (in Dutch).</ref> and gradual [[partition of Belgium|secession]] of [[Flanders]] from [[Belgium]].<ref name=\"ManifestPoint3\">[http://www.n-va.be/files/default/nva_images/documenten/manifest.pdf Manifesto of the New Flemish Alliance] point 3: \"Flanders member state of the European Union\" (in Dutch).</ref>{{third-party inline|date=January 2017}} In recent years it has become the largest party of Flanders as well as of Belgium as a whole, and it participated in the [[Michel I Government|2014\u201318 Belgian Government]] until 9 December 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/europe/belgiums-ruling-coalition-collapses-over-un-pact-on-migration/2018/12/09/e9740cc2-fbc9-11e8-a17e-162b712e8fc2_story.html?noredirect=on|title=Belgium\u2019s ruling coalition collapses over U.N. pact on migration|date=9 December 2018|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the 2014 elections, the New Flemish Alliance is the largest Belgian / Flemish political party in the [[European Parliament]], with its four [[Member of the European Parliament|MEPs]] sitting with the [[European Conservatives and Reformists]] (ECR) [[Political groups of the European Parliament|parliamentary group]].\n\nThe party is also known for its insistence on the exclusive use of [[Dutch language|Dutch]], Flanders' sole official language, in dealings with government agencies, and for the promotion of the use of Dutch in Flanders.<ref name=\"ManifestPoint13\" /> The main objective of the party is to work on Flemish independence by gradually obtaining more powers for both Belgian communities separately.<ref name=\"beginselverklaring\">{{cite web|url=http://www.n-va.be/sites/default/files/documents/PDF/beginselverklaring0.1.pdf |title=Beginselverklaring N-VA |format=PDF |date= |accessdate=2017-01-16}}</ref> Furthermore, it emphasizes its non-revolutionary character (as opposed to the [[Far-right politics|far-right]] character of the [[Vlaams Belang]]) in order to legitimize increased Flemish autonomy.<ref>[http://www.n-va.be/files/default/generated/persbericht/Internationale%20persconferentie%20-%20Verklaring%20Bart%20De%20Wever.pdf Internationale persconferentie], N-VA.be. Retrieved on 2010-06-14.</ref>{{third-party inline|date=January 2017}}\nThe N-VA advocates [[free-market economics]], and their manifesto proposes immediate tax reductions to stimulate the economy.<ref>{{cite web|author=Alain Mouton |url=http://trends.knack.be/economie/nieuws/beleid/n-va-en-open-vld-beloven-bedrijven-het-aantrekkelijkste-economisch-klimaat/article-4000617205543.htm |title=Knack Magazine election manifesto review 2014 |publisher=Trends.knack.be |date=2014-05-08 |accessdate=2017-01-16}}</ref> The party previously advocated deepening ties with the European Union,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140426215538/http://english.n-va.be/en/about/faq|title=FAQ - Nieuw-Vlaamse Alliantie (N-VA)|date=26 April 2014|publisher=}}</ref><ref name=\"blogs.lse.ac.uk\">{{citeweb|url=https://blogs.lse.ac.uk/europpblog/2014/06/23/the-new-flemish-alliances-decision-to-join-the-ecr-group-says-more-about-belgian-politics-than-it-does-about-their-attitude-toward-the-eu/|title=The New Flemish Alliance\u2019s decision to join the ECR group says more about Belgian politics than it does about their attitude toward the EU|access-date=10 June 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref> but have shifted in recent years to a more \"eurorealist\" or \"eurocritical\" stance.<ref name=\"De Standaard\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.standaard.be/cnt/dmf20140618_01146790|title=N-VA kiest voor ECR-fractie in Europees Parlement|last=dgs|website=De Standaard|language=nl-BE|access-date=2018-12-21}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===Fall of the People's Union===\n{{Main|People's Union (Belgium)}}\nThe N-VA stems from the [[People's Union (Belgium)|People's Union]] ({{lang-nl|Volksunie}}, VU), a Belgian [[political party]] and broad electoral alliance of [[Flemish Movement|Flemish nationalists]]. Towards the end of the 20th century, with a steadily declining electorate and the majority of the party's [[federalism|federalist]] agenda implemented, friction between several wings of the People's Union emerged. In the beginning of the 1990s, [[Bert Anciaux]] became party president and led the party in an ever more [[Progressivism|progressive]] direction, combining the [[Social liberalism|social-liberal]] ideas of his new iD21-movement with the [[Regionalism (politics)|regionalist]] course of the People's Union. These experiments were opposed by the more traditional centre-right party base.\n\nTension rose towards the end of the decade, as [[Geert Bourgeois]], foreman{{Clarify|date=November 2015}} of the traditional and centre-right nationalist wing, was elected chairman by party members, in preference to the incumbent and progressive [[Patrik Vankrunkelsven]]. Factions subsequently clashed multiple times, over the future course of the party and possible support for current [[State reform in Belgium#2001: The fifth state reform|state reform negotiations]]. On 13 October 2001 the party openly split into three factions: the progressive wing around [[Bert Anciaux]], which would later become the [[Sociaal-Liberale Partij|Spirit]] party; the conservative nationalist wing around [[Geert Bourgeois]]; and a centrist group opposing the imminent split. A party referendum was held on the future of the party. The right wing gained a substantial plurality of 47% and inherited the party infrastructure.<ref>{{cite book|title=New Parties in Old Party Systems|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YnLcAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA26|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-964606-7|page=26}}</ref> Since no faction got an absolute majority, however, the name ''Volksunie'' could no longer be used.\n\n===Foundation and the election threshold===\nIn the autumn of 2001, the New Flemish Alliance ({{lang-nl|Nieuw-Vlaamse Alliantie}}, N-VA) was founded. Seven members of parliament from the People's Union joined the new party. The new party council created a party [[manifesto]] and a statement of principles. The first party congress was held in May 2002, voting on a party program and permanent party structures. [[Geert Bourgeois]] was elected chairman.\n\nThe party participated in elections for the first time in the [[2003 Belgian federal election|2003 federal elections]], but struggled with the [[election threshold]] of 5%. This threshold was only reached in [[West Flanders]], the constituency of [[Geert Bourgeois]]. With only one federal representative and no senator, the party lost government funding and faced irrelevance.\n\n===Cartel with CD&V===\nIn February 2004, the N-VA entered into an [[electoral alliance]], commonly known in Belgium as a [[Kartel (electoral alliance)|cartel]], with the [[Christian Democratic and Flemish]] (CD&V) party, the traditionally largest party, which was then in opposition. They joined forces in the [[2004 Belgian regional elections|regional elections in 2004]] and won. Both parties joined the new Flemish government, led by CD&V leader [[Yves Leterme]]. [[Geert Bourgeois]] became a minister, and [[Bart De Wever]] became the new party leader in October 2004.\n\nThe cartel was briefly broken when the former right-wing liberal [[Jean-Marie Dedecker]] left the [[Open Vlaamse Liberalen en Democraten|Open Flemish Liberals and Democrats]] (Open VLD) and entered the N-VA on behalf of the party executive. However, the party congress did not put Dedecker on the election list, instead preferring to continue the cartel with CD&V, who had strongly opposed placing him on a joint cartel list. Dedecker saw this as a vote of no confidence, and left the party after only 10 days, to form his own party, [[Libertair, Direct, Democratisch|List Dedecker]] (LDD). Deputy leader Brepoels, who supported Dedecker, stepped down from the party board afterwards.\n\nIn the Belgian federal election of 2007 the CD&V/N-VA cartel won a major victory again, with a campaign focusing on good governance, state reform and the division of the electoral district [[Brussels-Halle-Vilvoorde]]. The N-VA won five seats in the [[Chamber of Representatives (Belgium)|Chamber of Representatives]] and two seats in the [[Senate (Belgium)|Senate]]. [[Yves Leterme]] initiated coalition talks, which repeatedly stalled (see [[2007\u20132008 Belgian government formation]]). On 20 March 2008, a new federal government was finally assembled. N-VA did not join this government, but gave its support pending state reform.\n\nThe cartel ended definitively on 24 September 2008, due to lack of progression in state reform matters and a different strategy on future negotiations. N-VA left the Flemish Government and gave up its support of Leterme at the federal level.\n\n===Mainstream party===\nIn the [[2009 Belgian regional elections|regional elections of June 2009]], N-VA  won an unexpected 13% of the votes, making them the winner of the elections, along with their old cartel partner CD&V. N-VA subsequently joined the government, led by [[Kris Peeters]] (CD&V). [[Bart De Wever]] chose to remain party leader and appointed [[Geert Bourgeois]] and [[Philippe Muyters]] as ministers in the [[Flemish Government]] and [[Jan Peumans]] as speaker of the [[Flemish Parliament]].\n\nIn December 2018, a political crisis emerged over whether to sign the [[Global Compact for Migration]]; N-VA was against this, whereas the other three parties in the federal government supported it. On 4 December 2018, the Prime Minister of Belgium, [[Charles Michel]], announced that the issue would be taken to parliament for a vote.<ref name=\"The Washington Post\">{{cite web |last1=Casert |first1=Raf |title=Dispute over UN migration pact fractures Belgian government |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/europe/belgian-government-fights-for-survival-over-un-migrants-pact/2018/12/04/6fca1aa0-f79c-11e8-8642-c9718a256cbd_story.html |publisher=The Washington Post |date=4 December 2018}}</ref> On 5 December, parliament voted 106 to 36 in favor of backing the agreement.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.france24.com/en/20181205-belgian-pm-wins-backing-un-migration-pact|title=Belgian PM wins backing for UN migration pact|date=5 December 2018|work=France 24|accessdate=6 December 2018}}</ref> Michel stated that he would endorse the pact on behalf of parliament, not on behalf of the divided government.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timesnownews.com/international/article/belgian-pm-charles-michel-wins-backing-for-un-migration-pact/326659|title=Belgian PM Charles Michel wins backing for UN migration pact|work=www.timesnownews.com|accessdate=6 December 2018}}</ref> Consequently, N-VA quit the federal government; the other three parties continue as a minority government ([[Michel II Government|Michel II]]).\n\nDuring the [[2019 Belgian federal election|2019 federal elections]] the party again polled in first place in the Flemish region but saw a decline in vote share for the first time, falling to 25.6% of the Flemish vote.\n\n==Foundation and ideology==\nThe New Flemish Alliance is a relatively young political party, founded in the autumn of 2001. Being one of the successors of the Volksunie (1954\u20132001), it is, however, based on an established political tradition. The N-VA works towards the same goal as its predecessor: to redefine Flemish nationalism in a contemporary setting. Party leader De Wever calls himself a conservative and a nationalist.<ref>[http://www.trouw.nl/achtergrond/deverdieping/article3035462.ece/_rsquo_Laat_Belgie_maar_rustig___verdampen_rsquo__.html Trouw: \"Laat Belgie maar rustig verdampen\"], last seen April 8th, 2010.</ref>\n\nThe N-VA has previously argued for a Flemish Republic as a member state of a democratic [[Federal Europe|European confederation]]. The party believes that the challenges of the 21st century can best be answered by strong communities and by well-developed international co-operation, a position which is reflected in their tagline: \"Necessary in Flanders, useful in Europe.\" ({{lang-nl|Nodig in Vlaanderen, nuttig in Europa}}.)\n\nLike its [[People's Union (Belgium)|People's Union]] predecessor, a label for the political orientation of the N-VA was difficult to find as the party initially combined [[socially liberal]], left- and right-wing policies. In its 2009 election programme for Flanders, the N-VA described itself as [[Economic liberalism|economically liberal]] and [[Environmentalism|ecologically green]]. The party supported [[public transport]], [[open source software]], [[renewable energy]] and taxing cars by the number of kilometres driven. It wanted more aid for developing countries and more compulsory measures to require that immigrants learn Dutch.{{Citation needed|date=February 2012}} The party has generally been supportive of LGBT rights.<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://english.n-va.be/news/high-profile-forum-on-lgbt-rights-in-brussels|title=High profile forum on LGBT rights in Brussels |work=N-VA|access-date= 24 February 2020|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nIn recent years, the party has been described as becoming more of a [[conservative]] party, as opposed to a progressive nationalist movement, and moving ideologically further to the right under the influence of [[Bart De Wever]] and [[Theo Francken]] by adopting tougher stances on immigration, integration of minorities, security, crime and terrorism.<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.politico.eu/article/bart-de-wever-jan-jambon-belgian-right-wing-party-fends-off-racism-accusations/|title=Belgian right wing party fends off racism accusations. |work=Politico|access-date=1 January 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref name=\"euobserver\">{{citeweb|url=https://euobserver.com/eu-elections/123886/|title=Belgians\u2019 pride in the EU quells Euroscepticism. |work=euobserver|access-date=1 January 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref> In 2018, the party opposed the [[Global Compact for Migration]] and subsequently withdrew its participation in the Belgian government in protest of its passing.<ref name=\"The Washington Post\"/> Some commentators have attributed these shifts as a response to a revival in support for the Flemish nationalist [[Vlaams Belang]], which also campaigned against the Migration Compact.<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://theglobalobservatory.org/2018/12/global-compact-migration-missed-opportunity-europe/|title=Global Compact for Migration \u2013 A Missed Opportunity for Europe.work=theglobalobservatory|access-date=2 January 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nIn terms of foreign policy the N-VA\u2019s stance on the [[European Union]] began as strongly [[pro-European]] in character and in 2010 the party called for \u201can ever stronger and more united Europe.\u201d However, the party has since shifted to a position of [[soft Euroscepticism]] by no longer endorsing a vision of a federal Europe, calling for more democratic reform of the EU and stating that economically unstable nations should leave the [[Eurozone]].<ref name=\"euobserver\"/><ref name=\"blogs.lse.ac.uk\"/> The party is critical of the EU's stance on illegal immigration (in particular its handling of the migrant crisis) and the role played by NGOs in picking up migrants. The N-VA argues that the EU should emulate the Australian system of border protection to reinforce its external border and work with nations outside of Europe to stem the flow of illegal migrants arriving by sea.<ref name=\"knack.be\">https://www.knack.be/nieuws/belgie/francken-wil-naar-australisch-asielmodel-0-asielverzoeken-in-brussel/article-normal-1080799.html </ref>\n\nAt European level, the N-VA is part of the [[European Free Alliance]] (EFA), a [[European political party]] consisting of [[Regionalism (politics)|regionalist]], pro-[[independence]] and [[Political parties of minorities|minority interest]] political parties, of which the [[People's Union (Belgium)|People's Union]] was a founder member. During the [[Seventh European Parliament|7th European Parliament]] of 2009\u20132014, the N-VA was a member of [[The Greens\u2013European Free Alliance]] (Greens/EFA) group in the European Parliament. However, following the [[2014 European Parliament election in Belgium|2014 European elections]], the N-VA announced it was moving to a new group and chose the [[European Conservatives and Reformists]] (ECR)<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.standaard.be/cnt/dmf20140618_01146790|title= N-VA kiest voor ECR-fractie in Europees Parlement |first= Johan |last= Van Overtveldt |date= 2014-06-18 |work= standaard.be |language= Dutch |trans-title= N-VA chooses ECR Group in the European Parliament |accessdate= 2014-06-18}}</ref> over the [[Alliance of Liberals and Democrats for Europe]].\n\n==Party chairmen==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" | Name !! Portrait !! From !! To\n|-\n| 1 || [[Geert Bourgeois]] || [[File:Geert Bourgeois.jpg|65px]]|| 2001 || 2004\n|-\n| 2 || [[Bart De Wever]] || [[File:BartDeWever.jpg|65px]]|| 2004 || ''present''\n|}\n\n==Electorate==\nIn the [[2003 Belgian federal election|federal elections]] in 2003 N-VA received 3.1% of the votes, but won only one seat in the federal parliament. In February 2004 they formed an electoral alliance (cartel) with the [[Christian Democratic and Flemish]] party (CD&V). The cartel won the elections for the Flemish Parliament. The N-VA received a total of 6 seats. However, on 21 September 2008 the N-VA lost its faith in the federal government and the following day minister [[Geert Bourgeois]] resigned. In a press conference he confirmed the end of the CD&V/N-VA cartel.\n\nIn the [[2004 European Parliament election in Belgium|2004 European elections]], N-VA had 1 MEP elected as part of the cartel with CD&V.\n\nIn the 10 June 2007 [[2007 Belgian federal election|federal elections]], the cartel won 30 out of 150 seats in the [[Chamber of Representatives (Belgium)|Chamber of Representatives]] and 9 out of 40 seats in the [[Senate (Belgium)|Senate]].\n\nIn the [[2009 Belgian regional elections|regional elections of 11 June 2009]], N-VA (now on its own after the split of the cartel with [[Christian Democratic and Flemish|CD&V]]) won an unexpected 13% of the votes, making them the winner of the elections along with their former cartel partner. In the [[2009 European Parliament election in Belgium|2009 European elections]] held on the same day, the N-VA had one MEP elected.\n\nIn the [[2010 Belgian federal election|2010 federal elections]], N-VA became the largest party of Flanders and of Belgium altogether.\n\nIn the [[2014 Belgian federal election|2014 federal elections]], N-VA increased their dominant position, taking votes and seats from the far-right [[Flemish Interest]]. In the simultaneous [[2014 Belgian regional elections|2014 regional elections]] and [[2014 European Parliament election in Belgium|2014 European elections]], the N-VA also became the largest party in the [[Flemish Parliament]] and in the Belgian delegation to the [[European Parliament]].\n\nIn the [[2019 Belgian federal election|2019 federal elections]] the party remained in first place in the Chamber of Representatives, European Parliament and Flemish Parliament, but saw a slight decline in vote share for the first time, obtaining 16.03% of the votes in the Federal Parliament. This was in part due to a sudden upsurge in support for the [[Flemish Interest]].\n\n[[File:Kamer-1978-2014.png|thumb|200px|The six biggest Flemish political parties and their results for the House of Representatives (Kamer). From 1978 to 2014, in percentages of the total vote in Belgium.]]\n\n==Electoral results==\n===Federal Parliament (''Federaal Parlement'')===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| colspan=8|Chamber of Representatives (''Kamer van Volksvertegenwoordigers'')\n|-\n! Election year\n! No. of<br />overall votes\n! % of<br />overall vote\n! % of language<br />group vote\n! No. of<br />overall seats won\n! No. of language<br />group seats won\n! +/\u2013\n! Government\n|-\n! [[2003 Belgian federal election#Results|2003]]\n| 201,399\n| 3.1%\n| \n| {{Composition bar|1|150|hex={{New_Flemish_Alliance/meta/color}}}}\n| <small>{{Composition bar|1|88|hex=Lightgrey}}</small>\n| \n| {{no2|in opposition}}\n|-\n! rowspan=2|[[2007 Belgian federal election#Chamber of Representatives|2007]]\n| 1,234,950\n| 18.5% \n|'''29.6% (1st)'''\n| {{Composition bar|5|150|hex={{New_Flemish_Alliance/meta/color}}}} \n| <small>{{Composition bar|5|88|hex=Lightgrey}}</small>\n| {{increase}} 4\n| {{no2|in opposition}}\n|-\n| colspan=7|<small>In cartel with [[Christian Democratic and Flemish|CD&V]]; 30 seats won by CD&V/N-VA.</small>\n|-\n! [[2010 Belgian federal election#Chamber of Representatives|2010]]\n| 1,135,617\n| 17.40%\n|'''27.8% (1st)'''\n| {{Composition bar|27|150|hex={{New_Flemish_Alliance/meta/color}}}}\n| <small>{{Composition bar|27|88|hex=Lightgrey}}</small>\n| {{increase}} 22\n| {{no2|in opposition}}\n|-\n! rowspan=2 |[[2014 Belgian federal election#Chamber of Representatives|2014]]\n| rowspan=2 | 1,366,073\n| rowspan=2 | 20.32%\n| rowspan=2 |'''32.5% (1st)'''\n| rowspan=2 | {{Composition bar|33|150|hex={{New_Flemish_Alliance/meta/color}}}}\n| rowspan=2 | <small>{{Composition bar|33|87|hex=Lightgrey}}</small>\n| rowspan=2 | {{increase}} 6\n| {{yes2|in coalition (2014-2018)}}\n|-\n| {{no2|in opposition (since 2018)}}\n|-\n! [[2019 Belgian federal election#Chamber of Representatives|2019]]\n| 1,086,787\n| 16.03%\n|'''25.6% (1st)'''\n| {{Composition bar|25|150|hex={{New_Flemish_Alliance/meta/color}}}}\n| <small>{{Composition bar|25|87|hex=Lightgrey}}</small>\n|