itics]]\n[[Category:European Free Alliance]]\n[[Category:Pro-independence parties]]\n[[Category:2001 establishments in Belgium]]\n[[Category:Conservative parties in Belgium]]\n", "name_user": "MWD115", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/New_Flemish_Alliance"}
{"title_page": "James Cameron Tudor", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| honorific-prefix = [[Sir]]\n| name        = James Cameron Tudor\n| image       = <!-- just the filename, without the File: or Image: prefix or enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| alt         = \n| caption     = \n| birth_name  = \n| birth_date  = {{Birth date|1919|10|18|df=yes}} \n| birth_place = [[St. Michael, Barbados]]\n| death_date  = {{Death date and age|1995|6|9|1919|10|18|df=yes}} \n| death_place = [[Bridgetown, Barbados]]\n| nationality = \n| other_names = \n| known_for   = \n| occupation  = Politician\n}}\nSir '''James Cameron Tudor''' (18 October 1919 \u2013 9 July 1995<ref name=\"Tudor\">{{cite web |url= http://rulers.org/indext2.html |title=Index Tj-Tz  |work=rulers.org |accessdate=19 July 2016}}</ref>) was a [[Barbados|Barbadian]] politician and diplomat, who was a founding member of the country's [[Democratic Labour Party (Barbados)|Democratic Labour Party]] in 1955. He served on the first Provisional General Council and as the first General Secretary.<ref name=DLP>{{cite web|title=The Party |url=http://www.dlpbarbadoscanada.com/the-party.html |website=[[Democratic Labour Party (Barbados)|Democratic Labour Party]] |accessdate=3 December 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120204033621/http://www.dlpbarbadoscanada.com/the-party.html |archivedate= 4 February 2012 }}</ref> He served as deputy prime minister, education minister, high commissioner to Britain, and [[United Nations]] ambassador, and was elected to both houses of the national legislature.<ref name=WP /> He also worked as a broadcaster, lecturer and journalist.{{cn|date=October 2016}}\n\nTudor was made a [[Companion of the Order of St Michael and St George]] in the [[1970 New Year Honours]],<ref>{{London Gazette  |issue=45005 |date=30 December 1969 |page=51 |supp=y}}</ref> and was promoted to a Knight Commander of the Order in the [[1987 New Year Honours|1987 list]].<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=50767 |date=30 December 1986 |page=39 |supp=y |nolink=yes}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nBorn in [[St. Michael, Barbados]] in 1919, Tudor was educated at [[Harrison College (Barbados)|Harrison College]], Barbados, and at [[Keble College, Oxford]],{{cn|date=October 2016}} where in 1942 he became the first Black person elected president of the [[Oxford Union]].<ref name=Roberts>Pamela Roberts, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=KrvABQAAQBAJ&pg=PT159&lpg=PT159&dq=%22James+cameron+tudor%22+oxford&source=bl&ots=y8cwuLvVbq&sig=LfkTruAtghxwnaSSnMKLhn7LY64&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiq35GdorPPAhWEJcAKHfAwB90Q6AEIOjAJ#v=onepage&q=%22James%20cameron%20tudor%22%20oxford&f=false ''Black Oxford: The Untold Stories of Oxford University's Black Scholars''], Oxford: Signal Books, 2013.</ref> After receiving a master's degree in history and politics in 1944,<ref name=WP /> he returned to Barbados and taught at [[Combermere School]] (1946\u201348) and in [[British Guiana]] at Queens School (1948\u201351).{{cn|date=October 2016}}\n\nHe was elected to the Barbados House of Assembly in 1951. He was a founding member in 1955 of the [[Democratic Labour Party (Barbados)|Democratic Labour Party]],<ref name=Roberts /> which assumed power in 1961 and led the former British colony to independence in 1966.<ref name=WP /> \n\nHe served as Deputy [[Prime Minister]],<ref>{{cite book |title=Foreign Service Journal |year=1972 |publisher=[[American Foreign Service Association]]}}</ref> twice served as [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs, Foreign Trade and International Business (Barbados)|Foreign Minister of Barbados]]<ref>{{cite web |url= http://rulers.org/fm1.html |title=Foreign ministers A\u2013D |work=rulers.org |accessdate=19 July 2016}}</ref> (1971\u201372, 1986\u20131989),<ref name=\"Tudor\"/> [[Education Minister]]<ref>{{cite book |title=Almanac of Current World Leaders, Vols 10-11 |year=1967 |publisher=International Academy at Santa Barbara |page=13}}</ref> (1961\u201367),<ref name=\"Tudor\"/> as Barbados' [[High Commission of Barbados, London|High Commissioner to the United Kingdom]]<ref name=\"Obit\">{{cite news |title=Obituary: Sir James Cameron Tudor |newspaper=[[Toledo Blade]] |date=11 July 1995}}</ref> (1972\u201375), and High Commissioner to Canada (1990\u20131992),<ref name=\"Tudor\"/> and was the [[Permanent Representative of Barbados to the United Nations|Permanent Representative to the United Nations]]<ref name=\"Obit\"/> (1976\u20131979).<ref name=\"Tudor\"/>\n\nHe died in hospital in [[Bridgetown]], Barbados, aged 75, following a heart attack.<ref name=WP>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/local/1995/07/12/deaths/b9a98d2f-fa39-4c5c-b54e-446b3b84c7be/ \"Sir James C. Tudor\"], ''Washington Post'', 12 July 1995.</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tudor, James Cameron}}\n[[Category:1919 births]]\n[[Category:1995 deaths]]\n\n[[Category:Barbadian knights]]\n[[Category:Leaders of the Democratic Labour Party (Barbados)]]\n[[Category:Permanent Representatives of Barbados to the United Nations]]\n[[Category:High Commissioners of Barbados to the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:High Commissioners of Barbados to Canada]]\n[[Category:Knights Commander of the Order of St Michael and St George]]\n[[Category:People educated at Harrison College (Barbados)]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Keble College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the Oxford Union]]\n\n{{Law-bio-stub}}\n{{Barbados-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name        = James Cameron Tudor\n| image       = <!-- just the filename, without the File: or Image: prefix or enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| alt         = \n| caption     = \n| birth_name  = \n| birth_date  = {{Birth date|1919|10|18|df=yes}} \n| birth_place = [[St. Michael, Barbados]]\n| death_date  = {{Death date and age|1995|6|9|1919|10|18|df=yes}} \n| death_place = [[Bridgetown, Barbados]]\n| nationality = \n| other_names = \n| known_for   = \n| occupation  = Politician\n}}\nSir '''James Cameron Tudor''' (18 October 1919 \u2013 9 July 1995<ref name=\"Tudor\">{{cite web |url= http://rulers.org/indext2.html |title=Index Tj-Tz  |work=rulers.org |accessdate=19 July 2016}}</ref>) was a [[Barbados|Barbadian]] politician and diplomat, who was a founding member of the country's [[Democratic Labour Party (Barbados)|Democratic Labour Party]] in 1955. He served on the first Provisional General Council and as the first General Secretary.<ref name=DLP>{{cite web|title=The Party |url=http://www.dlpbarbadoscanada.com/the-party.html |website=[[Democratic Labour Party (Barbados)|Democratic Labour Party]] |accessdate=3 December 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120204033621/http://www.dlpbarbadoscanada.com/the-party.html |archivedate= 4 February 2012 }}</ref> He served as deputy prime minister, education minister, high commissioner to Britain, and [[United Nations]] ambassador, and was elected to both houses of the national legislature.<ref name=WP /> He also worked as a broadcaster, lecturer and journalist.{{cn|date=October 2016}}\n\nTudor was made a [[Companion of the Order of St Michael and St George]] in the [[1970 New Year Honours]],<ref>{{London Gazette  |issue=45005 |date=30 December 1969 |page=51 |supp=y}}</ref> and was promoted to a Knight Commander of the Order in the [[1987 New Year Honours|1987 list]].<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=50767 |date=30 December 1986 |page=39 |supp=y |nolink=yes}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nBorn in [[St. Michael, Barbados]] in 1919, Tudor was educated at [[Harrison College (Barbados)|Harrison College]], Barbados, and at [[Keble College, Oxford]],{{cn|date=October 2016}} where in 1942 he became the first Black person elected president of the [[Oxford Union]].<ref name=Roberts>Pamela Roberts, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=KrvABQAAQBAJ&pg=PT159&lpg=PT159&dq=%22James+cameron+tudor%22+oxford&source=bl&ots=y8cwuLvVbq&sig=LfkTruAtghxwnaSSnMKLhn7LY64&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiq35GdorPPAhWEJcAKHfAwB90Q6AEIOjAJ#v=onepage&q=%22James%20cameron%20tudor%22%20oxford&f=false ''Black Oxford: The Untold Stories of Oxford University's Black Scholars''], Oxford: Signal Books, 2013.</ref> After receiving a master's degree in history and politics in 1944,<ref name=WP /> he returned to Barbados and taught at [[Combermere School]] (1946\u201348) and in [[British Guiana]] at Queens School (1948\u201351).{{cn|date=October 2016}}\n\nHe was elected to the Barbados House of Assembly in 1951. He was a founding member in 1955 of the [[Democratic Labour Party (Barbados)|Democratic Labour Party]],<ref name=Roberts /> which assumed power in 1961 and led the former British colony to independence in 1966.<ref name=WP /> \n\nHe served as Deputy [[Prime Minister]],<ref>{{cite book |title=Foreign Service Journal |year=1972 |publisher=[[American Foreign Service Association]]}}</ref> twice served as [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs, Foreign Trade and International Business (Barbados)|Foreign Minister of Barbados]]<ref>{{cite web |url= http://rulers.org/fm1.html |title=Foreign ministers A\u2013D |work=rulers.org |accessdate=19 July 2016}}</ref> (1971\u201372, 1986\u20131989),<ref name=\"Tudor\"/> [[Education Minister]]<ref>{{cite book |title=Almanac of Current World Leaders, Vols 10-11 |year=1967 |publisher=International Academy at Santa Barbara |page=13}}</ref> (1961\u201367),<ref name=\"Tudor\"/> as Barbados' [[High Commission of Barbados, London|High Commissioner to the United Kingdom]]<ref name=\"Obit\">{{cite news |title=Obituary: Sir James Cameron Tudor |newspaper=[[Toledo Blade]] |date=11 July 1995}}</ref> (1972\u201375), and High Commissioner to Canada (1990\u20131992),<ref name=\"Tudor\"/> and was the [[Permanent Representative of Barbados to the United Nations|Permanent Representative to the United Nations]]<ref name=\"Obit\"/> (1976\u20131979).<ref name=\"Tudor\"/>\n\nHe died in hospital in [[Bridgetown]], Barbados, aged 75, following a heart attack.<ref name=WP>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/local/1995/07/12/deaths/b9a98d2f-fa39-4c5c-b54e-446b3b84c7be/ \"Sir James C. Tudor\"], ''Washington Post'', 12 July 1995.</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tudor, James Cameron}}\n[[Category:1919 births]]\n[[Category:1995 deaths]]\n\n[[Category:Barbadian knights]]\n[[Category:Leaders of the Democratic Labour Party (Barbados)]]\n[[Category:Permanent Representatives of Barbados to the United Nations]]\n[[Category:High Commissioners of Barbados to the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:High Commissioners of Barbados to Canada]]\n[[Category:Knights Commander of the Order of St Michael and St George]]\n[[Category:People educated at Harrison College (Barbados)]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Keble College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the Oxford Union]]\n\n{{Law-bio-stub}}\n{{Barbados-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Josharaujo1115", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added \"Sir\" prefix in infobox", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_Cameron_Tudor"}
{"title_page": "Alexander Prusin", "text_new": "'''Alexander Victor Prusin''' (born [[Lviv|Lviv, Ukraine]];<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://usobit.com/2018/08/alexander-victor-prusin-august-1-1955-august-13-2018-age-63/|title=Alexander Victor Prusin August 1 1955 August 13 2018 (age 63), death notice, USA|date=2018-08-15|work=United States Obituary Notices|access-date=2018-10-22|language=en-US}}</ref>  (1 August 1955 - 13 August 2018) was a [[professor]] of history at the [[New Mexico Institute of Mining and Technology]] from 2001 to 2018.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nmt.edu/news/2018/alexander_prusin_passes_away.php|title=Beloved History Professor, Alexander Prusin, Passes Away: New Mexico Tech|website=www.nmt.edu|language=en-US|access-date=2018-10-22}}</ref> He specialized in the history of [[Russia]] and [[Eastern Europe]], [[nationalism]], [[ethnic conflict]], and [[genocide]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Works ==\n\n* The Lands Between: Conflict in the [[East Europe]]an Borderlands, 1870-1992 (2010)\n* Nationalizing a Borderland: War, [[Ethnicity]], and Anti-Jewish [[pogrom|Violence]] in [[East Galicia]], 1914\u20131920 (2016)\n* Serbia under the [[Swastika]]: A [[Occupation of Serbia by Nazi Germany|World War II Occupation]] (2017)\n* Justice Behind the [[Iron Curtain]]: [[Nazis]] on Trial in [[Communist Poland]] (2018)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Prusin, Alexander}}\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:2018 deaths]]\n[[Category:American people of Ukrainian descent]]\n[[Category:New Mexico Institute of Mining and Technology faculty]]\n[[Category:American historians]]\n\n\n{{edu-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Alexander Victor Prusin''' (born [[Lviv|Lviv, Ukraine]];<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://usobit.com/2018/08/alexander-victor-prusin-august-1-1955-august-13-2018-age-63/|title=Alexander Victor Prusin August 1 1955 August 13 2018 (age 63), death notice, USA|date=2018-08-15|work=United States Obituary Notices|access-date=2018-10-22|language=en-US}}</ref>  (1 August 1955 - 13 August 2018) was a [[professor]] of history at the [[New Mexico Institute of Mining and Technology]] from 2001 to 2018.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nmt.edu/news/2018/alexander_prusin_passes_away.php|title=Beloved History Professor, Alexander Prusin, Passes Away: New Mexico Tech|website=www.nmt.edu|language=en-US|access-date=2018-10-22}}</ref> He specialized in the history of [[Russia]] and [[Eastern Europe]], [[nationalism]], [[ethnic conflict]], and [[genocide]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Works ==\n\n* The Lands Between: Conflict in the [[East Europe]]an Borderlands, 1870-1992 (2010)\n* Nationalizing a Borderland: War, [[Ethnicity]], and Anti-Jewish [[pogrom|Violence]] in [[East Galicia]], 1914\u20131920 (2016)\n* Serbia under the [[Swastika]]: A [[Occupation of Serbia by Nazi Germany|World War II Occupation]] (2017)\n* Justice Behind the [[Iron Curtain]]: [[Nazis]] on Trial in [[Communist Poland]] (2018)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Prusin, Alexander}}\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:2018 deaths]]\n[[Category:American people of Ukrainian descent]]\n[[Category:New Mexico Institute of Mining and Technology faculty]]\n[[Category:American historians]]\n\n\n{{edu-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alexander_Prusin"}
{"title_page": "Thaddeus Gromada", "text_new": "'''Thaddeus V. Gromada''' is a Polish-American historian. He is a professor emeritus of European history at the [[New Jersey City University]], a Former Executive Director and President of the [[Polish Institute of Arts & Sciences of America]] (PIASA) and the [[Polish American Historical Association]] and a Trustee and Vice Chair of The [[Kosciuszko Foundation]]. His scholarly interests are focused on areas such as Polish and Polish-American 20th century history.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aseees.org/membership/thaddeus-gromada|title=Thaddeus Gromada {{!}} ASEEES|website=www.aseees.org|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://polishamericanstudies.org/text/11/past-officers.html|title=Polish American Historical Association|website=polishamericanstudies.org|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://tadgromada.wordpress.com/about/ Thaddeus Gromada's homepage]\n\n{{US-historian-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Thaddeus V. Gromada''' is a Polish-American historian. He is a professor emeritus of European history at the [[New Jersey City University]], a Former Executive Director and President of the [[Polish Institute of Arts & Sciences of America]] (PIASA) and the [[Polish American Historical Association]] and a Trustee and Vice Chair of The [[Kosciuszko Foundation]]. His scholarly interests are focused on areas such as Polish and Polish-American 20th century history.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aseees.org/membership/thaddeus-gromada|title=Thaddeus Gromada {{!}} ASEEES|website=www.aseees.org|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://tadgromada.wordpress.com/about/ Thaddeus Gromada's homepage]\n\n{{US-historian-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Piotrus", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thaddeus_Gromada"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Iowa", "text_new": "{{short description|Details of ongoing pandemic in Iowa, United States}}\n{{Current disaster|event=pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Iowa\n| map1            = \n| places          = \n| legend1         = \n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Iowa]], U.S.\n| first_case      = [[Iowa City, Iowa|Iowa City]]\n| arrival_date    = March 8, 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=03|day1=8|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin          = \n| confirmed_cases = 786<ref name=\"idph-official\">{{cite web |title=Emerging Health Issues - Novel Coronavirus\n|url=https://idph.iowa.gov/Emerging-Health-Issues/Novel-Coronavirus |publisher=Iowa Department of Public Health |accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n| suspected_cases = \n| recovery_cases  = 46\n| deaths          = 14<ref name=\"kwqc.com\">https://www.kwqc.com/content/news/Additional-COVID-19-cases-in-Iowa-additional-deaths-confirmed-569380611.html</ref>\n| total_ili       = \n| website         = [https://idph.iowa.gov/Emerging-Health-Issues/Novel-Coronavirus Iowa Department of Public Health]\n}}\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have reached the U.S. state of [[Iowa]] in March 2020. The first known cases were three individuals who had traveled on a cruise in [[Egypt]] before returning home to [[Johnson County, Iowa|Johnson County]] on March 3.\n\n==Timeline==\n* March 3 - The first known cases were three individuals who had traveled on a cruise in [[Egypt]] before returning home to [[Johnson County, Iowa|Johnson County]] on March 3.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/4fed9d219a5c62f884f4eae081ddfa9b|title=Iowa governor announces first 3 COVID-19 cases in state|date=2020-03-08|website=AP NEWS|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n* March 9 \u2013 Proclamation of Disaster Emergency signed by Governor [[Kim Reynolds]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.weareiowa.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/8-iowans-test-postivie-for-coronavirus-covid-19/524-982d69c7-c93d-4bac-b65c-96006fbc6ddb|title=32 test negative, 8 test postive for COVID-19|website=weareiowa.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-28|first1=Hollie|last1=Schlesselman|date=2020-03-09}}</ref>\n*March 15 \u2013 Governor Reynolds recommends closing schools for four weeks. The state is developing legislation to provide child care during the emergency, including food for low-income students. The total number of confirmed coronavirus infections in the state increases to 22.<ref>[https://idph.iowa.gov/News/ArtMID/646/ArticleID/158307/Gov-Reynolds-recommends-Iowa-schools-close-for-four-weeks-will-hold-a-press-conference-tomorrow-31520 Gov. Reynolds recommends Iowa schools close for four weeks, will hold a press conference tomorrow (3/15/20)] Author: Polly Carver-Kimm, Iowa Department of Public Health, March 15, 2020</ref>\n*March 25 - Number of cases in Iowa reached 145, and one fatality reported in [[Dubuque County, Iowa|Dubuque County]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kcrg.com/content/news/21-additional-positive-COVID-19-cases-in-Iowa-569093311.html|title=21 additional positive COVID-19 cases in Iowa|date=2020-03-25|website=kcrg.com|language=english|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-25|first1=Jay|last1=Greene}}</ref>\n*March 26 - Governor expands upon previous Covid-19 disaster proclamations to halt non-essential surgeries.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.desmoinesregister.com/story/news/health/2020/03/26/iowa-governor-kim-reynolds-daily-covid-19-news-conference-coronavirus/2914636001/|title=Iowa orders additional retail closures, halts elective and nonessential surgeries and dental procedures|last=Richardson|first=Ian|work=Des Moines Register|language=en|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n*March 27 - Governor's office asserts:  \"[The] Proclamation suspends all nonessential or elective surgeries and procedures until April 16th, that includes surgical abortion procedures\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.desmoinesregister.com/story/news/health/2020/03/27/coronavirus-in-iowa-surgical-abortion-suspended-kim-reynolds-non-essential-surgery-proclamation/2930439001/|title=Governor's office says order suspending 'non-essential' surgery includes halting surgical abortions|last=Rodriguez|first=Barbara|work=Des Moines Register|language=en|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n*March 28 - The number of coronavirus cases in Iowa reaches 298.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n*March 29 - Number of cases in Iowa reached 336, and a fourth fatality reported in [[Linn County, Iowa|Linn County]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.swiowanewssource.com/coronavirus/article_eea0d864-2c81-51ec-88f9-f150edddae57.html|title=Fourth person dies from COVID-19 in Iowa|last=|first=|date=2020-03-29|website=swiowanewssource.com|language=english|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n*April 1 - Number of cases reached 549, and the number of fatalities reached 9.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.kwqc.com/content/news/Iowa-confirms-52-new-coronavirus-cases-two-more-deaths-569285521.html |title = Iowa confirms 52 new coronavirus cases, two more deaths}}</ref>\n*April 4 - Number of cases reached 786, and the number of fatalities reached 14.<ref name=\"kwqc.com\">https://www.kwqc.com/content/news/Additional-COVID-19-cases-in-Iowa-additional-deaths-confirmed-569380611.html</ref>\n\n==Statistics==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United States/Iowa medical cases}}\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:right\"\n! colspan=\"3\" |Coronavirus disease 2019 (COVID-19) cases in Iowa<ref name=\"idph-official\" />\nUpdated April 4, 2020\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" |County\n! scope=\"col\" |Confirmed Cases\n!Deaths\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Adair County, Iowa|A