February 2012}}\n{{Infobox game\n| title = ''Monopoly Here and Now: The World Edition''\n| subtitle =\n| image_link =| image_caption = The ''Monopoly Here and Now: The World Edition'' Game Box\n| designer =\n| illustrator =\n| publisher=[[Parker Brothers]]\n| players = 2\u20136\n| setup_time = 5\u201315 minutes\n| playing_time = About 1.5 hours\n| random_chance = High ([[dice]] rolling, card drawing)\n| skills = Negotiation, basic resource management\n| footnotes =\n| bggid =\n| bggxrefs =\n}}\nIn 2008, Hasbro released ''Monopoly Here and Now: The World Edition''. This world edition features top locations of the world. The locations were decided by votes over the Internet. The result of the voting was announced on August 20, 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ctv.ca/servlet/ArticleNews/story/CTVNews/20080820/monopoly_cities_080820 |title=Montreal top property in new ''Monopoly'' game \u2013 CTV.ca. Retrieved 2008/08/20 01:14&nbsp;pm UTC |publisher=Ctv.ca |date=August 20, 2008 |accessdate=June 10, 2009}}</ref>\n\nOut of these, [[Gdynia]] is especially notable, as it is by far the smallest city of those featured and won the vote thanks to a spontaneous, large-scale mobilization of support started by its citizens. The new game uses its own currency unit, the Monopolonian (a game-based take on the Euro; designated by '''<s>M</s>'''). The game uses said unit in millions and thousands. As seen below, there is no dark purple color-group, as that is replaced by brown, as in the European version of the game.{{citation needed|date=February 2012}}\n\nIt is also notable that three cities ([[Montreal]], [[Toronto]], and [[Vancouver]]) are from Canada and three other cities (Beijing, Hong Kong, and Shanghai) are from the People's Republic of China. No other countries are represented by more than one city.{{citation needed|date=February 2012}}\n\nOf the 68 cities listed on Hasbro Inc.'s website for the vote, [[Jerusalem]] was chosen as one of the 20 cities to be featured in the newest ''Monopoly'' World Edition.<ref name=\"MSNBC\">[http://www.nbcnews.com/id/23281286 ''Monopoly'' Contest Stirs Up Jerusalem Conflict], Associated Press, published February 21, 2008.</ref> Before the vote took place, a Hasbro employee in the London office eliminated the country signifier \"Israel\" after the city, in response to pressure from pro-[[Palestinian people|Palestinian]] [[advocacy group]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jergames.blogspot.com/2008/02/from-hasbro-regarding-removal-of-israel.html |title=From Hasbro, regarding removal of Israel from World Monopoly vote |date=February 20, 2008}}</ref> After the Israeli government protested, Hasbro Inc. issued a statement that read: \"It was a bad decision, one that we rectified relatively quickly. This is a game. We never wanted to enter into any political debate. We apologize to our ''Monopoly'' fans.\"<ref name=\"MSNBC\" />\n\n{{Clear}}\n{{hidden\n| style = border:1px solid silver; width: 100%;\n| headerstyle = background: lightblue; font-size: 110%;\n| contentstyle = text-align: center;\n| header = ''Monopoly Here and Now: The World Edition'' (2008)\n| content =\n{{Monopoly board layout\n |Edition =\n |Banner = MONOPOLY<br />Here and Now:<br />The World Edition\n |corner_1 = Collect <s>M</s>2<small>M</small> salary as you pass<br />'''GO'''\n |corner_2 = In Jail/Just Visiting\n |corner_3 = Free Parking\n |corner_4 = Go To Jail\n\n |spaces_horizontal = 9\n |spaces_vertical = 9\n\n |Color_101 = SaddleBrown |Space_101 = [[Gdynia]]<br /><s>M</s>600<small>K</small>\n |Color_102 =             |Space_102 = [[Community Chest cards|Community Chest]]\n |Color_103 = SaddleBrown |Space_103 = [[Taipei]]<br /><s>M</s>600<small>K</small>\n |Color_104 =             |Space_104 = [[Income tax|Income Tax]]<br />pay <s>M</s>2<small>M</small>\n |Color_105 =             |Space_105 = [[Rail transport|''Monopoly'' Rail]]<br /><s>M</s>2<small>M</small>\n |Color_106 = SkyBlue     |Space_106 = [[Tokyo]]<br /><s>M</s>1<small>M</small>\n |Color_107 =             |Space_107 = [[Chance cards|Chance]]<div style=\"font:bold 16pt times new roman,serif;color:#c00;\">?</div>\n |Color_108 = SkyBlue     |Space_108 = [[Barcelona]]<br /><s>M</s>1<small>M</small>\n |Color_109 = SkyBlue     |Space_109 = [[Athens]]<br /><s>M</s>1.2<small>M</small>\n |Color_110 =             |Space_110 =\n |Color_111 =             |Space_111 =\n |Color_112 =             |Space_112 =\n |Color_201 =             |Space_201 =\n |Color_202 =             |Space_202 =\n |Color_203 =             |Space_203 =\n |Color_204 = #ff0080 |Space_204 = [[Istanbul]]<br /><s>M</s>1.4<small>M</small>\n |Color_205 =             |Space_205 = [[Solar energy|Solar Energy]]<br /><s>M</s>1.5<small>M</small>\n |Color_206 = #ff0080 8|Space_206 = [[Moscow]]<br /><s>M</s>1.4<small>M</small>\n |Color_207 = #ff0080 |Space_207 = [[Toronto]]<br /><s>M</s>1.6<small>M</small>\n |Color_208 =             |Space_208 = [[Air travel|''Monopoly'' Air]]<br /><s>M</s>2<small>M</small>\n |Color_209 = Orange      |Space_209 = [[Rome]]<br /><s>M</s>1.8<small>M</small>\n |Color_210 =             |Space_210 = [[Community Chest cards|Community Chest]]\n |Color_211 = Orange      |Space_211 = [[Shanghai]]<br /><s>M</s>1.8<small>M</small>\n |Color_212 = Orange      |Space_212 = [[Vancouver]]<br /><s>M</s>2<small>M</small>\n\n |Color_301 = Red         |Space_301 = [[Sydney]]<br /><s>M</s>2.2<small>M</small>\n |Color_302 =             |Space_302 = [[Chance cards|Chance]]<div style=\"font:bold 16pt times new roman,serif;color:#1e55d5;\">?</div>\n |Color_303 = Red         |Space_303 = [[New York City|New York]]<br /><s>M</s>2.2<small>M</small>\n |Color_304 = Red         |Space_304 = [[London]]<br /><s>M</s>2.4<small>M</small>\n |Color_305 =             |Space_305 = [[Cruise ship|''Monopoly'' Cruise]]<br /><s>M</s>2<small>M</small>\n |Color_306 = Yellow      |Space_306 = [[Beijing]]<br /><s>M</s>2.6<small>M</small>\n |Color_307 = Yellow      |Space_307 = [[Hong Kong]]<br /><s>M</s>2.6<small>M</small>\n |Color_308 =             |Space_308 = [[Wind power|Wind Energy]]<br /><s>M</s>1.5<small>M</small>\n |Color_309 = Yellow      |Space_309 = [[Jerusalem]]<br /><s>M</s>2.8<small>M</small>\n |Color_310 =             |Space_310 =\n |Color_311 =             |Space_311 =\n |Color_312 =             |Space_312 =\n |Color_401 = Green       |Space_401 = [[Paris]]<br /><s>M</s>3<small>M</small>\n |Color_402 = Green       |Space_402 = [[Belgrade]]<br /><s>M</s>3<small>M</small>\n |Color_403 =             |Space_403 = [[Community Chest cards|Community Chest]]\n |Color_404 = Green       |Space_404 = [[Cape Town]]<br /><s>M</s>3.2<small>M</small>\n |Color_405 =             |Space_405 = [[Spaceflight|''Monopoly'' Space]]<br /><s>M</s>2<small>M</small>\n |Color_406 =             |Space_406 = [[Chance cards|Chance]]<div style=\"font:bold 16pt times new roman,serif;color:#c00;\">?</div>\n |Color_407 = Blue        |Space_407 = [[Riga]]<br /><s>M</s>3.5<small>M</small>\n |Color_408 =             |Space_408 = Super Tax<br />pay <s>M</s>1<small>M</small>\n |Color_409 = Blue        |Space_409 = [[Montreal]]<br /><s>M</s>4<small>M</small>\n |Color_410 =             |Space_410 =\n |Color_411 =             |Space_411 =\n |Color_412 =             |Space_412 =\n}}\n}}\n\nA similar online vote was held in early 2015 for an updated version of the game. The resulting board should be released worldwide in late 2015.{{Update inline|date=September 2017}} Lima, Peru won the vote and will hold the Boardwalk space.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/votemonopolyrw|title=MONOPOLY Here & Now|work=BuzzFeed}}</ref>\n\n===Deluxe editions===\nHasbro sells a ''Deluxe Edition'', which is mostly identical to the classic edition but has wooden houses and hotels and gold-toned tokens, including one token in addition to the standard eleven, a railroad [[locomotive]]. Other additions to the ''Deluxe Edition'' include a card carousel, which holds the title deed cards, and money printed with two colors of ink.<ref>{{cite web|title=MONOPOLY \u2013 Deluxe Edition|url=http://www.hasbro.com/monopoly/en_US/shop/details.cfm?R=8EE06EFB-6D40-1014-8BF0-9EFBF894F9D4:en_US|accessdate=1 August 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 1978, retailer [[Neiman Marcus]] manufactured and sold an all-chocolate edition of ''Monopoly'' through its [[Neiman Marcus#\"His and Hers\" & \"Fantasy\" gifts|''Christmas Wish Book'']] for that year. The entire set was edible, including the money, dice, hotels, properties, tokens and playing board. The set retailed for $600.<ref>{{Cite book | author=Orbanes, Philip | title=The Monopoly Companion | edition=First | publisher=Bob Adams, Inc. | year=1988 | page=[https://archive.org/details/monopolycompanio0000orba/page/20 20] | isbn=1-55850-950-X | url=https://archive.org/details/monopolycompanio0000orba/page/20 | author-link=Philip Orbanes }}</ref>\n\nIn 2000, the [[FAO Schwarz]] store in New York City sold a custom version called ''One-Of-A-Kind Monopoly'' for $100,000.<ref>[http://www.findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0EIN/is_2000_Sept_19/ai_65295755/pg_3 Archived article] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050115102011/http://www.findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0EIN/is_2000_Sept_19/ai_65295755/pg_3 |date=January 15, 2005 }} from ''Business Wire'', stored at Findarticles.com. Retrieved January 1, 2006.</ref> This special edition comes in a locking [[briefcase|attach\u00e9 case]] made with Napolino leather and lined in suede, and features include:\n* 18-[[carat (purity)|carat]] (75%) gold tokens, houses, and hotels\n* [[Rosewood]] board\n* Street names written in [[gold leaf]]\n* [[Emerald]]s around the Chance icon\n* [[Sapphire]]s around the Community Chest\n* [[Rubies]] in the brake lights of the car on the Free Parking Space\n* The money is real, negotiable [[United States currency]]\n\nThe ''[[Guinness Book of World Records]]'' states that a set worth $2,000,000 and made of 23-carat gold, with rubies and sapphires atop the chimneys of the houses and hotels, is the most expensive ''Monopoly'' set ever produced.<ref>[http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/content_pages/record.asp?recordid=43436 Most Expensive ''Monopoly'' Set world record.] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150209000057/http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/content_pages/record.asp?recordid=43436 |date=February 9, 2015 }}</ref> This set was designed by artist [[Sidney Mobell]] to honor the game's 50th anniversary in 1985, and is now in the Smithsonian Institution.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smithsonian-institution/the-jeweled-art-of-sidney-mobell-86945772/|title=The Jeweled Art of Sidney Mobell|last=Stromberg|first=Joseph|work=Smithsonian|access-date=2017-12-07|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n''[[Wired magazine|Wired]]'' magazine believes ''Monopoly'' is a poorly designed game. Former Wall Streeter Derk Solko explains, \"Monopoly has you grinding your opponents into dust. It's a very negative experience. It's all about cackling when your opponent lands on your space and you get to take all their money.\"<ref name=\"Wired\" />\n\nMost of the three to four-hour average playing time is spent waiting for other players to play their turn. \"Board game enthusiasts disparagingly call this a 'roll your dice, move your mice' format.\"<ref name=\"Wired\">{{cite journal|last=Curry |first=Andrew |url=https://www.wired.com/gaming/gamingreviews/magazine/17-04/mf_settlers?currentPage=2 |title=Monopoly Killer: Perfect German Board Game Redefines Genre |journal=Wired |date=January 4, 2009 |accessdate=June 10, 2009}}</ref>\n\nThe hobby-gaming community [[BoardGameGeek]] is especially critical.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boardgamegeek.com/thread/330653/why-hobby-gamers-dont-like-monopoly|title=Why Hobby Gamers Don't Like Monopoly \u2013 Monopoly \u2013 BoardGameGeek|website=boardgamegeek.com|access-date=September 2, 2018}}</ref> User reviews of Monopoly rank the game among the 20 worst games out of nearly 10,000 ranked in the database with an average rating of 4.36 out of 10 from over 25,000 reviews.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boardgamegeek.com/boardgame/1406/monopoly|title=Monopoly Board Game 1933|website=boardgamegeek.com|access-date=September 2, 2018}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/future/article/20200219-why-monopoly-is-such-a-bad-game|title=How to win Monopoly in the shortest possible time|last=Park|first=William|website=www.bbc.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-01}}</ref>\n\n==Monopoly Metaphors and Idioms==\n* [[Rich Uncle Pennybags]], also known as \"Mr. Monopoly\", the game's mascot character\n* [[Get Out of Jail Free card]], a popular metaphor for something that will get one out of an undesired situation\n* [[Monopoly money]], a derisive term to refer to money not really worth anything, or at least not being used as if it is worth anything. It could also allude to colorful currency notes used in some countries.\n* \"'''Do not pass Go. Do not collect $200'''\" is a phrase used in ''Monopoly'' that has become widely used in popular culture to describe an action forced upon a person that has only negative results.<ref name=\"Colarusso1992\">{{cite book|author=Calvin A. Colarusso|title=Child and Adult Development: A Psychoanalytic Introduction for Clinicians|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ldMAqxhKB4gC&pg=PA88|accessdate=25 June 2013|date=30 September 1992|publisher=Springer|isbn=978-0-306-44285-8|page=88}}</ref><ref name=\"Bucci2008\">{{cite book|author=Steve Bucci|title=Credit Repair Kit For Dummies|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=m2Xx4mUB5RQC&pg=PT179|accessdate=25 June 2013|date=28 July 2008|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=978-0-470-27673-0|page=179}}</ref> The phrase comes from the game's Chance and Community Chest cards, which a player must draw from if they land on specific spaces. Each deck has a card that reads \"GO TO JAIL: Go directly to Jail. Do not pass Go. Do not collect $200.\"<ref name=\"Sommers-FlanaganSommers-Flanagan2012\">{{cite book|author1=John Sommers-Flanagan|author2=Rita Sommers-Flanagan|title=Counseling and Psychotherapy Theories in Context and Practice: Skills, Strategies, and Techniques|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RMclh6zR3LEC&pg=PA361|accessdate=25 June 2013|date=10 February 2012|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=978-1-118-28904-4|page=361}}</ref> Early in the game, going to jail usually hurts a player as it prevents them from moving, which regularly leads to earning $200 from passing Go, and from landing on and buying property, though in the later game, jail prevents them from landing on others' developed property and having to pay rent. The cited phrase, \"Do not pass Go. Do not collect $200\", distinguishes the effect from other cards that move players; other cards use the phrasing \"Advance to [a particular location]\", which does allow the player to collect $200 if they pass Go during the advance. The phrase is used in popular culture to denote a situation in which there is only one immediate, highly unfavorable, irreversible outcome and has been described as a \"harsh clich\u00e9\".<ref name=\"Serim2011\">{{cite book|author=Ferdi Serim|title=Digital Learning: Strengthening and Assessing 21st Century Skills, Grades 5-8|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LjehHsQt0cEC&pg=PT138|accessdate=25 June 2013|date=14 December 2011|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=978-1-118-13107-7|page=138}}</ref><ref name=\"SYH-20130610\">{{cite news|url=https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/harmony-now-name-of-the-game-20130609-2nxy8.html|title=Harmony now the name of the game|last=Morris|first=Linda|date=2013-06-10|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|accessdate=25 June 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"NAF-20130507\">{{cite web|url=http://higheredwatch.newamerica.net/blogposts/2013/the_academic_graveyard_shift_irs_provides_guidance_on_identifying_institutional_peers|title=The Academic Graveyard Shift: IRS Provides Guidance on Identifying Institutional Peers|last=Lounder|first=Andrew|date=2013-05-07|publisher=[[New America Foundation]]|accessdate=25 June 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130913054902/http://higheredwatch.newamerica.net/blogposts/2013/the_academic_graveyard_shift_irs_provides_guidance_on_identifying_institutional_peers|archivedate=13 September 2013}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n'''Notes'''\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n'''Bibliography''' <!-- need to be used in ref. inline & removed; Philip Orbanes sources removed as he worked for Parker Brothers & current works at Winning Moves, a Hasbro licencee for Monopoly -->\n* Doll, Jen. \"An Anti-Capitalist Woman Invented Monopoly and a Man Got All the Credit\", ''The New Republic'' Feb. 5, 2015 [https://newrepublic.com/article/120933/mary-pilons-monopolists-review online]\n* Pilon, Mary, ''The Monopolists: Obsession, Fury, and the Scandal Behind the World's Favorite Board Game'' (Bloomsbury, 2015)\n* ''Monopoly as a Markov Process'', by R. Ash and R. Bishop, ''[[Mathematics Magazine]]'', vol. 45 (1972) pp.&nbsp;26\u201329.\n* ''Take a Walk on the Boardwalk'', by S. Abbott and M. Richey, ''[[College Mathematics Journal]]'', vol. 10, no. 3 (May, 1997) pp.&nbsp;162\u2013171.\n* {{Cite book| author=Anspach, Ralph | title=The Billion Dollar MONOPOLY Swindle | edition=Second | publisher=Xlibris Corporation | year=2000 | isbn=0-7388-3139-5| author-link=Ralph Anspach }}{{Self-published inline|certain=yes|date=December 2017}}\n* {{Cite book | author=Brady, Maxine | title=The Monopoly Book: Strategy and Tactics of the World's Most Popular Game | edition=First hardcover | publisher=D. McKay Co. | year=1974 | isbn=0-679-20292-7 | url=https://archive.org/details/monopolybookstra00brad }}\n* {{Cite book| author=Darzinskis, Kaz | title=Winning Monopoly: A Complete Guide to Property Accumulation, Cash-Flow Strategy, and Negotiating Techniques When Playing the Best-Selling Board Game | edition=First | publisher=Harper & Row, New York | year=1987 | isbn=0-06-096127-9}}\n* {{Cite boo